35. Search Insert Position
Problem

Given a sorted array of distinct integers and a target value:

Return the index if the target is found.
If not found, return the index where it should be inserted to maintain the sorted order.

Required Time Complexity: O(log n)

Key Observation

The array is already sorted.

Instead of checking every element one by one, we can use Binary Search to either:

Find the target.
Determine the correct insertion position.
Binary Search Approach
Steps
Initialize low = 0 and high = n - 1.
Find the middle element.
If nums[mid] == target, return mid.
If target > nums[mid], search the right half.
If target < nums[mid], search the left half.
If the target is not found, return low.
Code
class Solution {
    public int searchInsert(int[] nums, int target) {
        int low = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1;

        while(low <= high) {
            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            if(nums[mid] == target) {
                return mid;
            }
            else if(nums[mid] < target) {
                low = mid + 1;
            }
            else {
                high = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return low;
    }
}
Why Return low?

The most important concept in this problem:

When Binary Search ends without finding the target:

high < low

At that point:

high points to the last element smaller than the target.
low points to the first element greater than the target.

Therefore, low is exactly the position where the target should be inserted.

